Model:Package.name: mapping
Model:Package.annotation: Consolidation of the various mapping technologies. Most importantly, declaratively specifying a mapping from instances of one type to instances of another type must be covered.

Model:Package.name: wsdl
Model:Package.annotation: For web services interoperability. Depends on package xsd.

Model:Package.name: binding
Model:Package.annotation: Defines structures that can be used to bind functions to ports through which these functions can be invoked.

Model:Class.name: HttpBinding
Model:Class.annotation: Makes a function invokable through an HTTP requiest. A URL pattern can be specified that describes how URLs are to be matched and if/how parameter values are to be extracted from the URL.

Model:Class.name: HttpGetBinding
Model:Class.annotation: Makes a function invokable through an HTTP GET request. All arguments to the function must be marshalled in the URL. The UrlPattern defines how this happens.

Model:Class.name: HttpPutBinding
Model:Class.annotation: Allows for invoking a function through an HTTP POST request. Parameters to the function may either be encoded as part of the URL or may be transmitted in the request body, e.g., as a multipart message. The UrlPattern specifies how the URL is to be matched and if/which parameters are to be extracted from the URL. Additional parameters are expected in the request body in "default form."

Model:Class.name: UrlPattern
Model:Class.annotation: Can tell if a given URL matches the pattern and can help extract strings encoding specific parameters according to the pattern's specifications.

Model:Class.name: SimpleUrlPattern
Model:Class.annotation: Assumes that a static, fixed URL base is used to identify the binding. Parameter values are expected to follow in the query part of the URL (everything following the "?" character) in regular URL format (name1=value1&name2=value2...). Multiple occurrences of the same name create a multi-object for the respective parameter.

Model:Class.name: RestUrlPattern
Model:Class.annotation: Allows for the mapping of parameter values to parts of the base URL (preceding any query part, before the ? character, if any). This can help construct very short, easy to use URLs but comes at the price that special URL characters such as "/", "?" or '&' need to be URL-encoded correspondingly.
